On 31/03/2026 01:27 pm, CEO wrote:
>
> Dear SPINRISE Team,
>
> *I am sharing with you today the updated VB FSD Claude Guide — Version 2.
> *
> Attached: SPINRISE_VB_FSD_Claude_Guide_v2.docx
>
> Please read it fully before our Saturday session. *From the date of 
> this mail, v2 is the operative guide for all FSD documentation work in 
> SPINRISE. *V1 is superseded.
>
> *Why v2 exists
> *
> Version 2 was built entirely from what you told me.
>
> Three of you responded to my v1 circulation mail with observations 
> that were technically sharp and practically important. I want to 
> acknowledge each contribution by name, because the team should know 
> where v2 came from.
>
> *Sathishkumar *pointed out that the Kalsofte ERP distributes business 
> logic across Common modules, Class modules, and stored procedures — 
> not just the .frm file. He also highlighted that the TC (Transaction 
> Code) framework, which drives stock direction and accounting entries 
> across most of our modules, is largely implemented inside stored 
> procedures and would be missed entirely if only the form code was 
> submitted to Claude.
>
> *Mariyaiya *raised a more fundamental concern: that several PR, PO, 
> and Service PO screens have pending customer customisations in various 
> stages of stability. Submitting unstabilised code to Claude would 
> produce an FSD that documents an incomplete version of the screen — 
> and that instability would be permanently carried into SPINRISE.
>
> *Mariyaiya then went further.* Before I could even respond, he 
> produced a detailed critical analysis of the Purchase Requisition form 
> (tmpPoindent.frm) — a 9,108-line VB6 form — and shared it with 
> Muthuvel for IST review. That document, which I have gone through in 
> detail, identified 3 Critical defects, 3 High issues, 4 Medium issues, 
> and 2 Low issues in the form code. It also proposed the four-category 
> validation structure, the error message catalogue, the summary 
> scorecard, and the customer variation register — all of which are now 
> standard sections in the v2 FSD template.
>
> This is what good teamwork looks like. You were given a guide, you 
> used it on a real form, you found its limits, and you reported back 
> with precision. V2 is the direct result.
>
> *What is new in v2
> *
> For those who have read v1, here is what changed:
>
> Stage 0 is an entirely new mandatory phase that must be completed 
> before any FSD documentation begins. It covers code stabilisation 
> review, the screen readiness checklist, what to collect before opening 
> Claude (no longer just the .frm file — now includes Common modules, 
> Class modules, and all stored procedures), the TC framework reference 
> table, the customer variation register, and the dead code 
> identification step. Stage 0 is not optional. No FSD work begins on 
> any screen until Stage 0 is complete and TL-Dev has signed off.
>
> The follow-up prompts grew from three to six. Three new prompts were 
> added: one for Common and Class module logic, one for stored procedure 
> business rules, and one specifically for TC framework documentation. 
> These address the gap our first VB developer identified.
>
> The FSD template expanded from 8 sections to 14 sections. The six new 
> sections are the TC Framework, Common and Class Module Dependencies, 
> Error Message Catalogue, Customer Variation Register, SPINRISE 
> Migration Recommendations, and the Summary Scorecard. All six are 
> mandatory for transaction screens.
>
> The review chain is updated to four levels with the full IST 
> structured questionnaire (IST-1 to IST-7) that every Module Sr IST 
> Member must answer for each form they review.
>
> A new Section 8 documents eight known defect patterns to actively 
> search for in every VB6 form before submitting to Claude: 
> application-terminating End statements, hardcoded customer IDs, SQL 
> string concatenation, dead code blocks, inconsistent duplicate logic, 
> hardcoded file paths, missing transaction rollback, and typos in error 
> messages. Each pattern has the code signature to search for and the 
> action to take.
>
> Three quick reference cards are now at the back: the Developer Daily 
> Card, the four-column Reviewer Checklist, and the new Defect Patterns 
> Card. Print all three and keep them at your desk.
>
> *How I need each of you to use this guide
> *
> *Module VB Developers:*
> Section 3 (Stage 0) and Section 4 (the six steps and six prompts) are 
> your primary reference. Read them in full. Before you begin any FSD, 
> complete Stage 0 for that screen. Do not skip the Customer Variation 
> Register. Do not submit dead code. Run all six follow-up prompts, not 
> just the ones you feel are relevant.
>
> *Module Sr IST Members:*
> Section 6, Level 1 and the IST Structured Questionnaire (questions 
> IST-1 to IST-7) are your reference. For every FSD you review, answer 
> all seven questions. Section 8 (the defect patterns) is also important 
> for you — you are the person most likely to know from site experience 
> whether an application-terminating behaviour or a hardcoded customer 
> variation has caused problems in practice.
>
> *TL-IST:*
> Section 6, Level 2. Your role is cross-module consistency. Pay 
> particular attention to whether TC framework values and stored 
> procedure business rules are consistent with how the same logic is 
> handled in other modules you have implemented.
>
> *Project Manager:*
> Section 6, Level 3. Before any FSD reaches the CEO, confirm that all 
> 14 sections are complete, all IST questions are answered, the customer 
> variation register is filled, and the summary scorecard is present. An 
> incomplete FSD must be returned to the developer, not passed forward.
>
> *New Developer (Abinandan):*
> Welcome again. This guide is your primary reference for how SPINRISE 
> development works. Start by reading Section 3 (Stage 0) and Section 4. 
> The defect patterns in Section 8 will be particularly useful as you 
> begin reading Kalsofte VB6 code for the first time — you will 
> encounter all of these patterns. Now you know what to do with each one.
>
> *Jr Web Dev team:*
> Section 4, Step 6 and Section 7 are your references. The approved FSD 
> is your specification for React UI generation. Read Section 7 
> carefully — it shows you exactly what prompt to use when an FSD is 
> handed to you for code conversion.
>
> *A word on how we got here*
>
> When I shared v1, I said: this is version 1, your feedback will shape 
> version 2. You delivered. In less than a week, the team produced two 
> substantive pieces of written feedback and one detailed 12-section 
> critical analysis of a real form. That is not normal. Most teams wait 
> to be asked.
>
> *The quality of SPINRISE depends on the quality of our FSDs.* The 
> quality of our FSDs depends on the rigour of our process. The rigour 
> of our process depends on each of you taking ownership of the part 
> only you can contribute — your domain knowledge, your site experience, 
> your module expertise.
>
> V2 reflects all of that. Bring the same energy to v2 that produced it.
>
> *What I need from you *
>
> Every developer and IST member: have read v2 in full.
>
> Module VB Developers: bring your Stage 0 readiness assessment for your 
> assigned module — identify which screens are stable and which carry 
> pending customisations.
>
> Mariyaiya: bring the updated PR form critical analysis with the v2 FSD 
> template applied (14 sections). Muthuvel’s IST review of that 
> document, using the IST-1 to IST-7 questionnaire, should be underway.
>
> TL-Dev: bring the list of screens across all Phase 1 modules that have 
> pending customisations or open corrections. This becomes the Stage 0 
> stabilisation backlog.
>
> PM: activate the Stage 0 pre-sprint tracking in PULSE 360 for all 
> Phase 1 modules.
>
> *Saturday is when we lock the v2 process and start.*
>
> With appreciation for what this team has already contributed, and 
> confidence in what it will deliver,
> T Mani
